  <div class="tab-content active" id="tab-review">
    <div class="content-wrap">
      <div class="review-grid">
        <div class="review-body">
          <p>
           There are stories that entertain you, and then there are stories that drag you into the messiest, darkest corners of the human mind and refuse to let you look away. Crime and Punishment is the second kind. Dostoyevsky takes a single act, a murder Raskolnikov has convinced himself is philosophically justified, and then spends 550 pages dismantling every wall the man builds around it.
          </p>
          <p>
            The novel follows Raskolnikov, a broke, feverish former student in St. Petersburg who believes himself to be one of the rare people history permits to transgress ordinary moral law. He kills a pawnbroker. And then the real story begins, not the crime, but what the crime does to him. His mind turns on itself. The guilt he was certain he wouldn't feel arrives anyway, quietly at first and then all at once.
          </p>

          <div class="review-pull">
            "Pain and suffering are always inevitable for a large intelligence and a deep heart."
          </div>

          <p>
            What makes Dostoyevsky so suffocating in the best way is that Raskolnikov is not a monster. He is brilliant, proud, and completely undone by the gap between who he thought he was and who he turns out to be. That is the knife the book twists slowly. I went in expecting a thriller. I got a mirror.
          </p>
          <p>
            Dostoyevsky finished this novel weeks before his death. Knowing that changes
            everything and nothing — the book stands without biography, but knowing
            Yozo is Dostoyevsky gives it a weight that sits in your chest for days. This is
            not a comfortable book. It is the kind of book that knows your secrets.
            I read it in one sitting and then stared at the ceiling for a while.
          </p>
          <p>
            Read it if you have ever felt like you were watching human life from
            slightly outside of it. Read it if you have ever been the funniest person
            in a room and also the most lost. Read it if you can handle a book that
            will not offer you a resolution, only recognition.
          </p>
        </div>

