          <div class="theme-number">01</div>
          <div class="theme-name">The Superman Theory</div>
          <div class="theme-body">Raskolnikov believes certain extraordinary people exist above ordinary moral law  that history's great men commit acts others cannot and are justified by history. The entire novel is Dostoyevsky's methodical demolition of this idea, not through argument but through watching Raskolnikov live with what it costs him.</div>
          <div class="theme-quote">"Extraordinary men have the right to commit crimes and to transgress the law in various ways, simply because they are extraordinary."</div>
        </div>

        <div class="theme-card">
          <div class="theme-number">02</div>
          <div class="theme-name">Guilt as a physical force</div>
          <div class="theme-body">Dostoyevsky treats guilt not as an emotion but as a bodily experience. Raskolnikov sweats, faints, hallucinates, falls into fevers. The crime lives in his body before it lives in his confession. This is the novel's most modern psychological insight.</div>
          <div class="theme-quote">"He was in a terrible state — dishevelled, dirty, he had not undressed or washed for several days."</div>
        </div>

        <div class="theme-card">
          <div class="theme-number">03</div>
          <div class="theme-name">Redemption through suffering</div>
          <div class="theme-body">Sonya represents the novel's answer, that suffering accepted honestly, rather than rationalised away, is what leads a person back to themselves. Dostoyevsky is not being cruel. He genuinely believed this. Whether you agree with him or not, the argument is devastating.</div>
          <div class="theme-quote">"Suffering is the sole origin of consciousness."</div>
        </div>

        <div class="theme-card">
          <div class="theme-number">04</div>
          <div class="theme-name"> Poverty and the city</div>
          <div class="theme-body">St. Petersburg is not a backdrop. It is a pressure. The cramped apartments, the heat, the desperate people on every corner, Dostoyevsky uses the city to make Raskolnikov's mental state feel inevitable. This is what extreme poverty does to a brilliant mind with no outlet.</div>
          <div class="theme-quote">"There was a desperate claustrophobia in those streets — the stench, the crowds, the lime dust, the scaffolding, the bricks. That particular Petersburg stench combined with the heat was enough to make even a man who was used to it feel sick."</div>
        </div>

        <div class="theme-card">
          <div class="theme-number">05</div>
          <div class="theme-name">Pride as self-destruction</div>
          <div class="theme-body">Raskolnikov's real enemy is not the detective Porfiry. It is his own pride. He cannot confess because confession requires admitting he was wrong, and being wrong means the theory collapses, and the theory is all he has. Dostoyevsky understood that pride is just fear with better posture.</div>
          <div class="theme-quote">"I wanted to become Napoleon — that is why I killed her."</div>
        </div>

        <div class="theme-card">
          <div class="theme-number">06</div>
          <div class="theme-name">Faith vs Rationalism</div>
          <div class="theme-body">The novel is in constant argument with itself, Raskolnikov's cold utilitarian logic on one side, Sonya's irrational, unearnable faith on the other. Dostoyevsky doesn't pretend this is simple. But he knows which one he thinks keeps a person human.</div>
          <div class="theme-quote">"Love in action is a harsh and dreadful thing compared with love in dreams. (spoken by Sonya, drawn from Dostoyevsky's own notebooks for the novel)"</div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ══ CHARACTERS TAB ══════════════════════════════════════ -->
                                                                                                                                                                                                                          <div <div class="tab-content" id="tab-characters">
  <div class="content-wrap">
    <div class="char-list">

      <div class="char-card">
        <div>
          <div class="char-initial">R</div>
        </div>
        <div>
          <div class="char-name">Raskolnikov</div>
          <div class="char-role">Protagonist</div>
          <div class="char-body">Brilliant, feverish, and catastrophically proud. Raskolnikov is one of literature's great anti-heroes because Dostoyevsky refuses to make him simply evil or simply sympathetic. He is both, in shifting proportions, and the reader is never allowed to settle into a comfortable judgment.</div>
          <div class="char-insight">→ Aashima's note: Raskolnikov reminded me that intelligence without humility is just a more elaborate way to be lost.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="char-card">
        <div>
          <div class="char-initial" style="background:var(--ink3);">S</div>
        </div>
        <div>
          <div class="char-name">Sonya</div>
          <div class="char-role">The moral centre</div>
          <div class="char-body">A young woman forced into an impossible life who has kept her faith intact anyway. She is the novel's answer to everything Raskolnikov argues. Not because she wins the argument but because she doesn't need to — she just continues to exist, honestly, in front of him.</div>
          <div class="char-insight">→ Aashima's note: Sonya could have been written as a symbol. Dostoyevsky wrote her as a person. That's the difference.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="char-card">
        <div>
          <div class="char-initial" style="background:#7b8fa1;">P</div>
        </div>
        <div>
          <div class="char-name">Porfiry Petrovich</div>
          <div class="char-role">The detective</div>
          <div class="char-body">The most interesting cat-and-mouse in 19th century fiction. Porfiry knows. Raskolnikov knows he knows. The game is not about evidence — it is about who breaks first. Porfiry is brilliant and oddly kind, which makes him more frightening.</div>
          <div class="char-insight">→ Aashima's note: Porfiry wins by being patient. That is somehow the most unsettling thing about him.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="char-card">
        <div>
          <div class="char-initial" style="background:#9b7e6a;">D</div>
        </div>
        <div>
          <div class="char-name">Dunya</div>
          <div class="char-role">Raskolnikov's sister</div>
          <div class="char-body">Strong, clear-eyed, and one of the most underrated characters in the novel. She loves her brother without being destroyed by him, which is its own kind of extraordinary. Her subplot mirrors the main story's themes of dignity under pressure.</div>
          <div class="char-insight">→ Aashima's note: Dunya is who Raskolnikov could have been if the pride hadn't curdled into theory.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</div>

