      <div class="egg-reveal" id="egg-reveal">
        <h4>Before the novel, there was a firing squad</h4>
        <p>Fyodor  Dostoyevsky was arrested in 1849 for involvement in a socialist reading group. He was sentenced to death, taken to the execution ground, and had already watched two men before him be prepared for shooting, before a rider arrived with a last-minute commutation from the Tsar. He spent four years in a Siberian labour camp instead.</p>
        <p style="margin-top:0.75rem;">He never forgot what it felt like to stand in front of death and then be handed back his life. Raskolnikov's psychological obsession with transgression, punishment, and whether a person can earn their own survival, that is not invented. Dostoyevsky already knew what it felt like to be judged, condemned, and given an unexpected second chance. He spent the rest of his life writing about it.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="connections-section">
        <p class="conn-section-title">Films with a similar atmosphere</p>
        <div class="conn-grid">
          <div class="conn-card">
            <div class="conn-card-type">Film · France · 1959</div>
            <div class="conn-card-title">Pickpocket </div>
            <div class="conn-card-sub">Robert Bresson</div>
            <div class="conn-card-why">A man who believes he is intellectually above the law, told in cold, precise close-ups. Bresson never explains or moralises. The closest a film has ever come to Raskolnikov's interior logic.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="conn-card">
            <div class="conn-card-type">Film · USA · 1935</div>
            <div class="conn-card-title">Crime and Punishment</div>
            <div class="conn-card-sub">Josef von Sternberg</div>
            <div class="conn-card-why">The earliest major adaptation. Peter Lorre as Raskolnikov is genuinely unsettling, all nervous energy and barely contained collapse. Worth watching just for his performance.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="conn-card">
            <div class="conn-card-type">Film · UK · 2005</div>
            <div class="conn-card-title">Match Point </div>
            <div class="conn-card-sub">Woody Allen</div>
            <div class="conn-card-why">A man commits a crime he believes he can outthink his way through. The guilt arrives differently than he expected. Allen has said Dostoyevsky was the direct inspiration.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="connections-section">
        <p class="conn-section-title">Books in the same conversation</p>
        <div class="conn-grid">
          <div class="conn-card">
            <div class="conn-card-type">Novel · France · 1942</div>
            <div class="conn-card-title">The Stranger</div>
            <div class="conn-card-sub">Albert Camus</div>
            <div class="conn-card-why">Both Meursault and Yozo are alienated from normal human feeling, but where Meursault is cold, Yozo is overwhelmed. Two sides of the same rupture.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="conn-card">
            <div class="conn-card-type">Novel · USA · 1963</div>
            <div class="conn-card-title">The Bell Jar</div>
            <div class="conn-card-sub">Sylvia Plath</div>
            <div class="conn-card-why">Plath and Dostoyevsky are writing from the same interior — the precise, first-person account of a mind that cannot make peace with the world outside it.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="conn-card">
            <div class="conn-card-type">Novel · Russia · 1864</div>
            <div class="conn-card-title">Notes from Underground</div>
            <div class="conn-card-sub">Fyodor Dostoyevsky</div>
            <div class="conn-card-why">Written just before Crime and Punishment. The Underground Man is Raskolnikov before the murder, all the pride and the theory, none of the consequences yet. Read this first if you want to understand where Raskolnikov comes from</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="connections-section">
        <p class="conn-section-title">Music that matches the mood</p>
        <div class="conn-grid">
          <div class="conn-card">
            <div class="conn-card-type">Album · Russia · 1937</div>
            <div class="conn-card-title">Symphony No. 5 </div>
            <div class="conn-card-sub">Dmitri Shostakovich </div>
            <div class="conn-card-why">Written under political pressure, performed under surveillance. There is something in it that sounds exactly like Raskolnikov's mind, brilliant, controlled on the surface, barely holding together underneath.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="conn-card">
            <div class="conn-card-type">Album · USA · 1975</div>
            <div class="conn-card-title">The Köln Concert</div>
            <div class="conn-card-sub">Keith Jarrett</div>
            <div class="conn-card-why">Improvised piano, live, in one sitting. It moves between unbearable tension and something close to grace. The same arc the novel takes, just without words.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="conn-card">
            <div class="conn-card-type">Album · UK · 2011</div>
            <div class="conn-card-title">A Winged Victory for the Sullen</div>
            <div class="conn-card-sub">Erased Tapes</div>
            <div class="conn-card-why">Slow, heavy, beautiful ambient music that feels like guilt that has been sitting in a room for a long time. Perfect for the chapters where Raskolnikov is just lying in his apartment falling apart.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="connections-section">
        <p class="conn-section-title">Philosophy nearby</p>
        <div class="conn-grid">
          <div class="conn-card">
            <div class="conn-card-type">Philosophy · 19th century Russia</div>
            <div class="conn-card-title">Nihilism </div>
            <div class="conn-card-sub">Nietzsche</div>
            <div class="conn-card-why">Raskolnikov's superman theory is a dark cousin of Nietzschean philosophy, the idea that extraordinary individuals exist beyond ordinary moral constraints. Dostoyevsky was writing a rebuttal before Nietzsche had even finished the argument.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="conn-card">
            <div class="conn-card-title">Russian Orthodox Christianity</div>
            <div class="conn-card-why">Not an academic philosophy but the living worldview underneath the novel. Sonya's faith, the idea of redemption through suffering, the possibility of forgiveness,  none of it makes sense without understanding what Dostoyevsky actually believed. The novel is, among other things, a theological argument.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
